[src:interior-point-methods/interior-point-method] If we do not have such a point, we need to find one using a so-called **phase I method**.
[src:interior-point-methods/interior-point-method] A simple phase-I method is to solve the following convex program: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{minimize}}\quad &s\\{\text{subject to}}\quad &g_{i}(x)\leq s{\text{ for }}i=1,\dots ,m\end{aligned}}$ Denote the optimal solution by x*,*s**.
[src:interior-point-methods/interior-point-method] For this program it is easy to get an interior point: we can take arbitrarily *x*=0, and take *s* to be any number larger than max(*f*1(0),...,*fm*(0)).
[src:interior-point-methods/interior-point-method] Therefore, it can be solved using interior-point methods.
[src:interior-point-methods/interior-point-method] However, the run-time is proportional to log(1/*s**).
[src:interior-point-methods/interior-point-method] As s* comes near 0, it becomes harder and harder to find an exact solution to the phase-I problem, and thus harder to decide whether the original problem is feasible.
