[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Denoting by n the number of variables, *m* the number of inequality constraints, and L the number of bits of input to the algorithm, Karmarkar's algorithm requires $O(m^{1.5}n^{2}L)$ operations on $O(L)$ -digit numbers, as compared to $O(n^{3}(n+m)L)$ such operations for the ellipsoid algorithm.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] In "square" problems, when *m* is in O(*n*), Karmarkar's algorithm requires $O(n^{3.5}L)$ operations on $O(L)$ -digit numbers, as compared to $O(n^{4}L)$ such operations for the ellipsoid algorithm.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] The runtime of Karmarkar's algorithm is thus $O(n^{3.5}L^{2}\cdot \log L\cdot \log \log L),$ using FFT-based multiplication (see Big O notation).
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Karmarkar's algorithm determines the next feasible direction toward optimality and scales back by a factor 0 < γ ≤ 1.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Karmarkar also has extended the method to solve problems with integer constraints and non-convex problems.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] The affine-scaling method can be described succinctly as follows.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] While applicable to small scale problems, it is not a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] This figure shows each iteration of the algorithm as red circle points.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] The constraints are shown as blue lines.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] At the time he invented the algorithm, Karmarkar was employed by IBM as a postdoctoral fellow in the IBM San Jose Research Laboratory in California.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] On August 11, 1983 he gave a seminar at Stanford University explaining the algorithm, with his affiliation still listed as IBM.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] By the fall of 1983 Karmarkar started to work at AT&T and submitted his paper to the 1984 ACM Symposium on Theory of Computing (STOC, held April 30 - May 2, 1984) stating AT&T Bell Laboratories as his affiliation.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] After applying the algorithm to optimizing AT&T's telephone network, they realized that his invention could be of practical importance.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] In April 1985, AT&T promptly applied for a patent on his algorithm.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] The patent became more fuel for the ongoing controversy over the issue of software patents.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] This left many mathematicians uneasy, such as Ronald Rivest (himself one of the holders of the patent on the RSA algorithm), who expressed the opinion that research proceeded on the basis that algorithms should be free.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Even before the patent was actually granted, it was argued that there might have been prior art that was applicable.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Mathematicians who specialized in numerical analysis, including Philip Gill and others, claimed that Karmarkar's algorithm is equivalent to a projected Newton barrier method with a logarithmic barrier function, if the parameters are chosen suitably.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Furthermore, Karmarkar's contributions are considered far from obvious in light of all prior work, including Fiacco-McCormick, Gill and others cited by Saltzman.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] The patent was granted in recognition of the essential originality of Karmarkar's work, as U.S. patent 4,744,028: "Methods and apparatus for efficient resource allocation" in May 1988.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] AT&T designed a vector multi-processor computer system specifically to run Karmarkar's algorithm, calling the resulting combination of hardware and software KORBX, and marketed this system at a price of US$8.9 million.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] The patent itself expired in April 2006, and the algorithm is presently in the public domain.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] The United States Supreme Court has held that mathematics cannot be patented in *Gottschalk v.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Benson*, In that case, the Court first addressed whether computer algorithms could be patented and it held that they could not because the patent system does not protect ideas and similar abstractions.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Diehr*, the Supreme Court stated, "A mathematical formula as such is not accorded the protection of our patent laws, and this principle cannot be circumvented by attempting to limit the use of the formula to a particular technological environment.
[src:interior-point-methods/karmarkar-s-algorithm] Karmarkar's algorithm was used by the US Army for logistic planning during the Gulf War.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Allowing inequality constraints, the KKT approach to nonlinear programming generalizes the method of Lagrange multipliers, which allows only equality constraints.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Similar to the Lagrange approach, the constrained maximization (minimization) problem is rewritten as a Lagrange function whose optimal point is a global maximum or minimum over the domain of the choice variables and a global minimum (maximum) over the multipliers.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] The Karush–Kuhn–Tucker theorem is sometimes referred to as the saddle-point theorem.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] The KKT conditions were originally named after Harold W.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Tucker, who first published the conditions in 1951.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Later scholars discovered that the necessary conditions for this problem had been stated in an unpublished master's thesis by William Karush in 1939.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] where $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbf {X}$ is the optimization variable chosen from a convex subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , f is the objective or utility function, $g_{i}\ (i=1,\ldots ,m)$ are the inequality constraint functions and $h_{j}\ (j=1,\ldots ,\ell )$ are the equality constraint functions.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] The numbers of inequalities and equalities are denoted by m and $\ell$ respectively.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] (necessity) Suppose that $f(\mathbf {x} )$ and $g_{i}(\mathbf {x} )$ , $i=1,\ldots ,m$ , are convex in $\mathbf {X}$ and that there exists $\mathbf {x} _{0}\in \operatorname {relint} (\mathbf {X} )$ such that $\mathbf {g} (\mathbf {x} _{0})<\mathbf {0}$ (i.e., Slater's condition holds).
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Since the idea of this approach is to find a supporting hyperplane on the feasible set $\mathbf {\Gamma } =\left\{\mathbf {x} \in \mathbf {X} :g_{i}(\mathbf {x} )\leq 0,i=1,\ldots ,m\right\}$ , the proof of the Karush–Kuhn–Tucker theorem makes use of the hyperplane separation theorem.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] The system of equations and inequalities corresponding to the KKT conditions is usually not solved directly, except in the few special cases where a closed-form solution can be derived analytically.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] In general, many optimization algorithms can be interpreted as methods for numerically solving the KKT system of equations and inequalities.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Suppose that the objective function $f\colon \mathbb {R} ^{n}\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ and the constraint functions $g_{i}\colon \mathbb {R} ^{n}\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ and $h_{j}\colon \mathbb {R} ^{n}\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ have subderivatives at a point $x^{*}\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] In the particular case $m=0$ , i.e., when there are no inequality constraints, the KKT conditions turn into the Lagrange conditions, and the KKT multipliers are called Lagrange multipliers.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Primal stationarity states that the "force" of $\partial f(x^{*})$ is exactly balanced by a linear sum of forces $\partial h_{j}(x^{*})$ and $\partial g_{i}(x^{*})$ .
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Dual feasibility additionally states that all the $\partial g_{i}(x^{*})$ forces must be one-sided, pointing inwards into the feasible set for x .
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Complementary slackness states that if $g_{i}(x^{*})<0$ , then the force coming from $\partial g_{i}(x^{*})$ must be zero i.e., $\mu _{i}(x^{*})=0$ , since the particle is not on the boundary, the one-sided constraint force cannot activate.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] The necessary conditions can be written with Jacobian matrices of the constraint functions.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] One can ask whether a minimizer point $x^{*}$ of the original, constrained optimization problem (assuming one exists) has to satisfy the above KKT conditions.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] This is similar to asking under what conditions the minimizer $x^{*}$ of a function $f(x)$ in an unconstrained problem has to satisfy the condition $\nabla f(x^{*})=0$ .
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] For the constrained case, the situation is more complicated, and one can state a variety of (increasingly complicated) "regularity" conditions under which a constrained minimizer also satisfies the KKT conditions.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] In practice weaker constraint qualifications are preferred since they apply to a broader selection of problems.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] In some cases, the necessary conditions are also sufficient for optimality.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] In general, the necessary conditions are not sufficient for optimality and additional information is required, such as the Second Order Sufficient Conditions (SOSC).
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] For smooth functions, SOSC involve the second derivatives, which explains its name.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Similarly, if the objective function f of a minimization problem is a differentiable convex function, the necessary conditions are also sufficient for optimality.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] It was shown by Martin in 1985 that the broader class of functions in which KKT conditions guarantees global optimality are the so-called Type 1 **invex functions**.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] For smooth, non-linear optimization problems, a second order sufficient condition is given as follows.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] where only those active inequality constraints $g_{i}(x)$ corresponding to strict complementarity (i.e. where $\mu _{i}>0$ ) are applied.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] The solution is a strict constrained local minimum in the case the inequality is also strict.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] If $s^{T}\nabla _{xx}^{2}L(x^{*},\lambda ^{*},\mu ^{*})s=0$ , the third order Taylor expansion of the Lagrangian should be used to verify if $x^{*}$ is a local minimum.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Often in mathematical economics the KKT approach is used in theoretical models in order to obtain qualitative results.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] For example, consider a firm that maximizes its sales revenue subject to a minimum profit constraint.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Since $Q=0$ would violate the minimum profit constraint, we have $Q>0$ and hence the third condition implies that the first condition holds with equality.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Given this definition, each coefficient $\mu _{i}$ is the rate at which the value function increases as $a_{i}$ increases.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] Thus if each $a_{i}$ is interpreted as a resource constraint, the coefficients tell you how much increasing a resource will increase the optimum value of our function f .
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] This interpretation is especially important in economics and is used, for instance, in utility maximization problems.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] which are called the Fritz John conditions.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] This optimality conditions holds without constraint qualifications and it is equivalent to the optimality condition *KKT or (not-MFCQ)*.
[src:interior-point-methods/karush-kuhn-tucker-conditions] The KKT conditions belong to a wider class of the first-order necessary conditions (FONC), which allow for non-smooth functions using subderivatives.
